review.reviewBody: I would absolutely love this shoe, IF ONLY Hoka offered it in a Wide. I wanted to make them work so bad, I bought them anyway - but now my feet are killing me. Will be returning - do better Hoka!!
review.name: No Wide??

review.reviewBody: I wear an 8/8.5 mens shoe. Kaha's were comically narrow. Like, made for tiny women's feet. I dont have very wide feet either, though i am mostly flat footed. Hoka needs to offer "wide" in more styles that arent just low ankle sneakers. I returned them.
review.name: Very Narrow fit, returned them.

review.reviewBody: I have multiple pairs of Anacapa 2 Mid and Kaha 2 Mid 'S.. I switch them out daily, Being a large Man this helps them last. They have saved my Knee and feet it's true I just love them I am considering buying another Hoka Kaha 2 in the Barley color. That's another reason for multiple pairs the great color choices. My oldest pair are 3 years old newest less than one month
review.name: I have Bought this product Again and again . Haha 2 and

review.reviewBody: As we all age, our weight bearing feet become worn in the arch and joints...life. This shoe design simply attends to various foot movement mechanics including impact softening as well as heel strike, and they are neat looking. 1st shoe, (of many), that manage these issues and is the only shoe I can wear for distances. This is a champion design HOKA, don't change a thing...even your color range works!
review.name: I will buy again as long as they are not changed.

review.reviewBody: Normally I don't write reviews but these were worth it and more. Bought them for a Grand Teton National Park and Yellowstone trip. They are sturdy and absorb a lot of shock that thinner hiking shoes might not. Perfect for scrambling and feeling comfortable on rocky terrain. My girlfriend also got a pair. Stylish and saved our feet a lot of agony. It doesn't hurt that they look great and I wanted them in multiple colors.
review.name: Save Your Feet, Look Elite - Buy Hoka Kahas :)

review.reviewBody: This is my first pair of Hoka shoes and I am so pleased. These shoes are so comfortable and feel so right when im wearing them. I've had them for only 1 or 2 weeks now, I hope the wear factor is good also. So far very happy.
review.name: Very pleased

review.reviewBody: Toe box collapsed in the first week. A couple of hard seems make it less than ideal for comfort.
review.name: Could be better

review.reviewBody: These boots were the most comfortable I've had, but they only lasted five months before the outsole lost all of its tread and the shoe laces fell apart. I'm buying a second pair because of how comfortable they are, but knowing they will not last very long at all.
review.name: Great boot, but doesn't last

review.reviewBody: I need a waterproof Gore-Tex boot for working in the snow.
review.name: Need a smaller size

review.reviewBody: I would recomend replacing the shoe inserts if you buy these. They do seem pretty durable and are very lightweight. I tried the bondi sr before and I would highly recomend those instead. I bought these thinking they would be just as comfortable but with extra ankle support.
review.name: It hurts with the shoe inserts that come with it.

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] Such a cute little bag , perfect for the purse or to go anywhere, it comes with a good amount of bandaids  , in really happy with it!
review.name: Cute

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] Adventure Medical backyard adventure fox is a must have! I love this cute little medical pack. It is super cute, and easily clips to backpacks, purses, diaper bags, you name it! Inside there is bandages, hand sanitizer, and triple antibiotic ointment. Perfect for small scrapes on a small hike or playground trip (or if you're like me and seem to always need a bandage at home but never can find any!). There is room still for some smaller things too you could put in if you wanted. We dont leave home without this cute fox. And you'd never know it was my first aid kit!
review.name: Must have!

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] I absolutely love this little bag. It is so easy to carry around and has some important features inside that you might need. It's perfect to carry around in case of an emergency! I highly recommend it!
review.name: Great features!

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] This cute backyard adventure bear is a very cute way to carry first aid supplies for little kids, it comes with some little supplies for minor scratches and cuts but is a little bag that you can refill with your own supplies, perfect for trips to the park
review.name: Very useful

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] I got Backyard Adventure Bear as sample to try and opinion is my own.The Backyard Adventure Bear First Aid Kit for kids makes first aid fun and easy. Perfect for outdoor activities, this medical kit includes kid-friendly first aid supplies to treat cuts and scrapes in a cute woodland critter case. The carabiner makes it easy to clip this mini first aid kit to your child’s backpack for school field trips, family hikes, summer camp, or backyard adventures.
review.name: Adventure with bear 1st aid kit

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] Backyard Adventure Fox First Aid Kit comes with all kinds of great essential for on the go and for personal use. Nice to see and quite fox on it to help the kids stay calm. Comes with the aid you need for a accident. This was a free sample and my honest review.
review.name: Fun first ad

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] This is nice to add to our array of stuff we take out with us. Something easy for the kids to use and easy to “refill” and gives our kids a level of independence.
review.name: Precious

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] This first aid kit was super cute! The adorable bear shape made it very child friendly. It has everything a learning child needs to tend to minor scrapes, cuts, and bruises. It clips on perfectly to anything. You can put it on a backpack, purse, belt loop, or wherever!
review.name: So cute!

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] Love this little fox. Its super cute and I love that it had bandaid and ointments in it. It was super easy to hook onto my purse so I always have what I need in case one of my children needs it.
review.name: So cute

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] My daughter loves raccoons. We have them in the backyard and she watches them out the window. She was excited to get this little pouch. She took out the bandages and put them in the bathroom for everyone to use, and then attached the raccoon to her backpack to hold little things. Although she isn't using it for it's intended use, we still love it just the same. If you're looking for it to use as intended, I would suggest not letting your kids see it, or they may want it for their backpacks.
review.name: So cute!

review.reviewBody: Bought these for my husband who wears the same mtn bike clothes every week. He's 6'1 and about 170 pounds. A medium in everything and usually a 31/32 in pants. Purchased the L based on other reviews and they were still too tight in the straps and cut into his shoulders. Otherwise they fit. I just can't imagine the XL giving him the right amount of compression so sending these back.

review.itemreviewed: Mountain Liner Bib Short + Swat - Men's
Mountain Liner Bib Short + Swat - Men's
review.reviewBody: The shorts portion fit perfectly, but the actual bib straps were stretched to the max pulling the chamois up and too tight for comfort. I?m 6?2, 34? waist. I?m worried an XL would be too big in the waist for a relatively tall guy like me.
review.name: Short In The Body

review.itemreviewed: Mountain Liner Bib Short + Swat - Men's
review.reviewBody: These are comfortable bibs.  The size can feel small when you're off the bike, but once you're in the leaned over position the straps fit better and the bib is quite comfortable.  The thigh and back pockets are very convenient.  My issues are durability and the location of the fly.  The fly is cut a little high so peeing can be a bit of a battle.  The bibs are developing holes between the padding and the spandex/lycra of the bibs after only one season.  It's also a bit annoying that they're transparent.  Overall, the bibs are great for the price but don't expect them to last very long.
review.name: Comfortable but there are some issues

review.itemreviewed: Mountain Liner Bib Short + Swat - Men's
review.reviewBody: ive had a few pairs of the previous version of SWAT liner bib, solidly size medium (30" waist). The mediums were wayyy small in this version. Returning for Large.
review.name: smaller than the previous version

review.itemreviewed: Mountain Liner Bib Short + Swat - Men's
review.reviewBody:
I've been wearing these liner bibs under my Chrome bike shorts on both my road and mountain bike rides for the past couple of months and found it to be a super comfortable combo.  The fabric breathes well and I really like the padding and how it doesn't extend into the front of the shorts. 
The swat pockets are awesome also.  They can hold a good amount of stuff (gels, snacks, tube, etc.) and because they're affixed to the bibs, nothing moves or shifts around on your back like it sometimes can in the back pockets of a jersey.
I first purchased size Medium and ended up getting a Large since the Mediums felt just a little bit short in the body.   
Highly recommended.
review.name: Really nice
comment: Thank you so much for your review! We really appreciate the feedback. Glad to hear you were able to get the right size.

review.itemreviewed: Mountain Liner Bib Short + Swat - Men's
review.reviewBody:
Specialized nailed it. Truly. 

An amazing amount of pockets and one of the most breathable bibs I?ve used. I can carry a whole days worth of snacks and my camera all without the need for a hip pack. 

Easy access for when nature calls, and a nice chamois for a forward position while climbing to earn some turns.
review.name: The only mtb liner I?ll ever use.

review.itemreviewed: Mountain Liner Bib Short + Swat - Men's
review.reviewBody: Absolutely incredible! And they didn't put padding in the front! Finally the mountain bike clothing world is starting to make designs that make sense for men. There are a couple other companies doing the abbreviated chamois now and this is the best one I've tried. I tried swat bibs a few years ago and didn't like them, they were heavy and the mesh was stiff and weird fitting. These are light, comfortable, well ventilated. Also they aren't nearly so transparent as the pics make them look. Of course they go under your shorts but I was glad they didn't look goofy like those pictures. The chamois looks and feels thick but on the bike it felt minimal (in a good way). These are even better than the giro liners....which I love!  Sizing was definitely on the more relaxed side (a positive).
review.name: New favorite

review.itemreviewed: Mountain Liner Bib Short + Swat - Men's
review.reviewBody:
I do want to start this review by saying that I am typically not a fan of bibs because the shoulder straps get on my nerves after some time. Surprisingly enough I hardly noticed the straps on these bibs and didn't get bothered by them at all while riding.  The three pockets in the back easily have enough room to stash a cliff bar bottle and even my swat deflect jacket when I was not wearing it. Another pro is the bib back pockets are separated from the bottom part of the bib and allow easy access to the pockets if you wanted to throw on a part of shorts over the bibs.

My only qualm with these is I feel like the inseam is a little too short for me in a medium and generally wear a 32x32 in pants and feel like the chamois rides pretty tight in the groin region.

Also, I did see someone was asking about use for gravel grinding. I took these out for a 30-mile gravel grind split the time between being on road and chunky double track. While on the double track I definitely did wish that I had a thick chamois and would say if you are on a nice forest road they would be fine but if you are looking to grind some chunkier sections of trails a different chamois would provide more relief.
review.name: Solid construction and easy access

name: Mountain Liner Bib Short + Swat - Men's

review.reviewBody: I fell down some stairs in December 2021. I ended up in hospital for several months. I returned to my life with balance and steadiness issues, resulting from mild brain injury and concussion. I had physical therapy. i have long owned and work Teva sandals and shoes and some from "Keen". I also have macrophotography as a hobby. I have only begun to return to it recently, and need to avoid hiking trails for now. I have been in physical therapy and my balance is much better. I have suffered a few additional falls because of poor balance. What I wear is very important. I have found walking in Keen sandals can bring on unsteadiness. I recently switched to the Teva Outflow Universal Sandals. I still wear Keen indoors on rugs. The Teva Outflows are so much steadier that I bought a second pair. I would enclose a photo of the Outflow Sandals but I don't know how to attach it to thia review. Thanks Teva!

Uncomfortable straps, poor fit and finish, smells seems to be a feature of most beach sandals. These hiking sandals were available at a ridiculous sale price, so I tried again. WOW. I love these water sandals. They adjust easily and comfortably. Only worn them twice to the beach, but that's enough to know they are different than many other beach sandal brands that I've worn.

review.itemreviewed: S/Pro Supra Boa 130 GW Ski Boot - 2025 - Men's
review.reviewBody:
This boot hits the mark on a modern, powerful, comfortable, and well made resort boot. I have put in about a week of skiing on them now and have nothing but amazing things to say. I have a mid volume foot with a mid height instep and the fit is perfect for me. The BOA wraps around my foot snug and doesnt have any weird pressure points like typical buckles. The BOA also feels super solid and durable. Another big bonus is the grip walk, it is there for you on long walks to the back of the parking lot after bell to bell laps or tromping up the booter while passing your friends to get fresh tracks.

The 130 flex feels progressive yet powerful and I have loved the feedback this boot provides. It allows you to power from edge to edge, take big hits off trail and still have the control and feel you look for in a resort boot. Don't walk, run to get yourself a pair of these!
review.name: Exactly what I needed!

review.reviewBody: This is a nice mid weight riding jersey. Solid quality. Pay attention to US vs Euro sizing.
review.name: Great mid weight riding jersey

review.reviewBody:
Bought this late winter to wear in early spring and mid to late fall in the NE US.
Have worn it a few times this spring and very happy with the fit and warmth.  I like having my neck covered and this does the job.  High quality zipper.  Because it is high vis yellow and recommended to wash with like colors, I always wash alone on cold and dry alone on gently.
review.name: Great fit, great look, great function!

review.reviewBody: I absolutely love when a product supports its description and dedicated purpose! It’s a jersey, not a jacket!, and it does exactly what it supposed to do. Keep you warm and protected. No-not from a hurricane-duh. Coldish mornings/evenings,45-50 degrees.  mild wind, cloudy day. It’s perfect. (For me) is true to size. M-US/L-EU is exactly my size. Other brands fit tighter, their “M” and is too tight. Not this jersey. M-is a real M. Great quality and tailoring. Zipper closes and opens perfect. Pockets have plenty of room. And the yellow color is more than visible. I have no idea how other (reviewers) riders found anything wrong to complain. Not me. It is absolutely perfect. If you need a great warm quality jersey, this is the one!
review.name: Perfect Jersey!

review.reviewBody:
I tried on a L and M.
The medium was a bit tight but fine if you want an aero fit.  The large was more my preference; form fitting but a bit looser everywhere.  I had on a thin base layer when trying on both.
The quality is good with a nice thin thermal layer which was comfortable and should be warm.  Zip pocket is a nice add.  
I am 5'7" and about 160 lbs.  My chest is about 39-40 with 32 arm length.  
Looking forward to riding with this jersey in the cooler temps.  With another comparable Gore jersey I wear a base layer and a jacket when in the high 30's to 50 degrees..
review.name: Fit was fine

review.reviewBody: I've been pleased with other Gore Wear products, however, this instance of their C3 Thermal Jersey is a bit off in its proportions. I'm fairly lean and have been a solid "Medium" with many other lines. Here, to get the jersey zipped up I had to stretch it together making an uncomfortably - sausage casing, tight fit. A Large might have worked for a roomier mid-section - which I have no roundness to speak of, but the body length and arms would be too long. Guess one should be a little wary of clothing that is not modeled on a human being.
review.name: Tried it on, Fit was off

review.reviewBody: I got this for the upcoming Fall/Winter rides, it hasn't been there temperature wise yet, but upon trying it on it seems true to size L. Wear it with a base layer and I think I'll be good to go. Material is good quality.
review.name: Great for a cool ride

review.reviewBody:
Upon opening, this appeared very well made but proved to be some of the strangest sizing I've yet experienced in cycling clothes. And the sizing chart for this product is wayyyy off.

First, I ordered an XL (USA) based on the size chart (I'm 5'11" and 170 with a 41" chest and boxer-type build). The thing was massive - it would've fit a 46" chest with arms to match easily. I returned it right away.

I then meant to replace it with a L, and mistakenly ordered a M. (So, don't multi-task when ordering cycling gear!) I tried it on anyway and the body actually fit perfectly, but the arms were still huge! So, that's going back too.

If you have arms ridiculously out of proportion to your body, this might work for you. Or, maybe this was meant for cycling orangutans?
review.name: Nice quality; very strange sizing
comment: I agree with Eric, the proportions are off on this jersey.  I accidentally ordered an EU Small (US Xtra Small).  I tried it on and it was too small in the body, but the arms were too long!  Not by a little...  by at least an inch or two.  I was going to return it and get the US Small, but I fear the arms would be too baggy.

review.itemreviewed: 303 S Carbon Disc Brake Wheel - Tubeless
review.reviewBody:
303S wheelset is good to go. The factory tape is solid with no leaks. Freehub has some noise but is nice and quiet compared to my GRC1400 screamers. Bought these as a second set for tarmac. Installed road tires on them. I appreciate the lower noise level on downhill runs. The GRCs would drive me crazy while coasting downhill sections....too loud!

Anyways, great value wheel that is just as good as the other set I have that cost considerably more and they weigh about the same. 

30mm Contis spec'd at 30.5mm once installed.

Get'em and rip!
review.name: Great wheels!

review.itemreviewed: 303 S Carbon Disc Brake Wheel - Tubeless
review.reviewBody: These are fine. They look good, but the hub engagement is low and “clangy” with any dead space in the cadence. I am currently shopping for a nicer set of wheels and considering either selling these or replacing the hubs. End of day… I’d avoid them.
review.name: I Wish I Bought other Wheels

review.itemreviewed: 303 S Carbon Disc Brake Wheel - Tubeless
review.reviewBody: I've had these for the better part of two years, and they're great. I use them on my gravel bike. They're lighter than my aluminum gravel wheelset. They are also aero and reasonably stiff. I have swapped between 28mm road-type tubeless tires when I want to take the gravel bike on the road, and 40mm gravel tires for gravel. The wheels are at home on either terrain. The tubeless setup has been flawless. The biggest issue I have had is the freehub design is held in by friction and if it comes out you sometimes have to remove the entire cassette in order to get to properly re-seat the seal. (I thought I previously reviewed these but my review seems to have disappeared.)
review.name: Excellent for road or gravel

review.itemreviewed: 303 S Carbon Disc Brake Wheel - Tubeless
review.reviewBody: Wanted to love them but they are: pretty flexy when standing, heavier than expected and have a 3-pawl free hub that seems like it's made of cheese -- so soft the cassette cuts into it and can't be remove without he whole hub body pulling off every time, spilling the stupid palls out on the bench. Cheap for Zipp, but still not worth the price I'm afraid.
review.name: At least they say Zipp....

review.reviewBody: After about 17 years, my Mountain Hardwear Offwidth (XL) jacket finally failed. I was disappointed at the availability of similar (non-hooded, non-fleece, zippered chest and hand pockets) replacements. I was familiar with Kuhl based on a pair of their hiking pants and was confident with them generally. I am 6'2" 185 with wide shoulders and gangly arms. Mountain Hardwear has always had a good cut for me and most brands tend to be on the too-short or too-boxy side. I have only small notes for an overall fantastic jacket. First, the non-adjustable button cuffs and the lack of drawstring hems is a bit of a loss. While I did not use them often, they were occasionally very helpful. Second, the sleeves are adequate, but even going XL I could use a tad more sleeve length (it is occasionally, but rarely, noticeable). Last, the zipper for the chest pocket is on the smaller side- you get standard phone in it but it requires just a little bit of noticeable articulating- I may also come to appreciate the smaller size/opening in time, it is also not a big deal. Otherwise, the jacket is top shelf material and workmanship. I love the attention to detail with the cut of the jacket panels, the (feelingly) durable zipper, the fleece-lined collar, the chin zipper protector, the rugged yet muted styling, thick stitching, neutral lining, and the (de-facto) inside pockets. It leans on the style over function side of things, but for wearing everywhere and all the time (office, out, and outdoor), it's a tradeoff I'm actually valuing. The XL has the right amount of room for me with layering- I went with a Large for their Impakt Vest and that was the right size for just considering chest/length.
review.name: Quality, Fashion-Leaning Softshell

Black is fine, but I was excited to see this brown, especially since the accents match one of my nightshirts. These leggings fit just like my tried and true, but I do wish there would've been a closeup of the dotted/vented knit at the rear and calves, which is thinner than the rest of the material. review.reviewBody: bought to use on a nissan versa hatchback.  could not be more perfect for this car.  very stable and solid feeling. I never worried about the bikes.  on a versa hatchback the only thing to watch out for is the added weight to the hatchback.  the hatch will slam shut if you let it with an empty rack on it.  the arms fold down when not hauling bikes.  a good feature but watch your head when closing the hatch. i take the arms off when not hauling bikes.  It should be obvious but the rear wipers don't have room to swing with this installed but not a drawback.  overall a great product.

review.reviewBody: Needed a trunk rack to carry three bikes, and discovered this rack has been out for years with excellent performance.  Found it easy to install and load the bikes onto it.  During multiple trips involving highway driving, the rack performed superbly with not one stitch of damage to the car.  As an added bonus, discovered we did not need stabilizer bars for my wife's Fuji and my twin daughters' 20 inch bikes which remained level throughout each trip, although other bikes for women and girls may require using this device.  This rack remains a truly excellent product that will reliably perform very well carrying up to three bikes.
review.name: Great track record and excellent perforance

review.reviewBody: Although the bike shop had a limited selection I was more than satisfied with my purchase. The rack was easy to setup and remove as well as the ease of lowering the arms when not in use. The fasteners held the bikes securely on bumpy, unpaved Vermont roads. Paved roads are a snap. Only two seasons old, waiting on it's reliability over time.

review.reviewBody: I did not use these to climb in rather only writing a review to help those looking for the right size. I consistently wear a women's size 8 and ordered these in a size women's 8.5 which is a men's 7.5. This shoe is considered unisex so goes off men's sizes. It was a tough decision as I was between this shoe and and the Evolv's Elektra. The fit on this was a good snug (not uncomfortable like other climbing shoes I have tried) and I felt they would likely stretch but when it came down to it my feet felt better in the other shoes. I'd say if you want a snug fit go a half size up from your regular shoe size or if you want a more relaxed fit go a whole size up. Maybe in the future I'll order a whole size up. The shoe offered all around comfort for the slightly snug fit.
review.name: Sizing Guide

review.reviewBody:
I decided to try these after wearing through my  first pair of climbing shoes. I have some food issues (bunions) and find most all shoes excruciatingly painful. I had tried on a pair of the Mundaka's some  time earlier and remembered how comfortable they were for such an aggressive shoe, and looked into the line more for their basic shoe, bringing me here. I would say the rubber is a little stickier than the Tarantulace, but not by a lot. The shoe is also more flexible, but again, but by a lot. These are my gym shoes, but I also wear them outside most of the time and I use them for all but my project grades (which isn't that high- 10a-10d depending on the style). I've had them nearly two years now, with probably 1 year of consistent use and the rubber is holding strong. 

I don't really know how to gauge climbing shoe sizing. i have these in a 7 and my street shoe is an 8. They're comfortably snug, but I don't wear my shoes very tight due to the aforementioned bunions.
review.name: Excellent Jack of all Trades

review.reviewBody:
These padded briefs are well made. The cut, the fit, and the material are excellent. 

However, the chamois is extremely thin, and it is sewn into the briefs so far back that it does not provide any benefit to the areas that are actually engaging with the saddle. Rearward oriented chamois, even when they are much too thin, give the feeling that one is wearing diapers. Forward oriented chamois that do not hug the bottom and protect the soft tissue do not feel like diapers because they do not excessively cover the bottom. These briefs have a distinctively rearward oriented chamois. 

Regarding sizing: I am 165lbs, with a very athletic build. In NIKE Pro shorts, I take an XL. In most American made road cycling shorts, I take a medium. In Euro road shorts I take a large. I ordered an XL based on the measurement chart and because I did not want the waistband to cut into my belly. They were too big.

review.reviewBody: After trying another brand that is supposed to have great nutrition and being unable to take more than two bites I was skeptical about freeze dried meals.   The chicken teriyaki I just made was very good.  I did soak it 9 minutes instead of 5 but I will definitely order more.
review.name: Surprisingly Tasty

review.reviewBody: I’ve tried the chicken teriyaki for the first time, the meal was delicious and easy to make. I’ve been eating the meals at work while in meetings or at my desk as my schedule been a bit hectic. I’ve even shared my meal with coworkers who now have purchased their own meals. It’s to a point that i don’t want to cook again lol. Keep the great going ReadyWise.
review.name: The food was extremely tasty, easy steps to eat.

review.reviewBody: We’re storing up meals for hurricane season and this will be one for sure. Filling and tasty. Living on the coast of NC, we get hit by hurricanes almost every year so we have to prepare for periods of power outages. I have a military background and have lived off C rations, LRRPS and MREs for long periods. These are much better.
review.name: Good meal for two

review.reviewBody: I'm on my second pair and wear them commuting an hour each way to work when temps are 30s & 40s... I pair them with over the calf winter wool socks.  (I don't like full length winter bibs with ankle zippers.)  I find they are not warm enough once temps get down into mid 20s.  These are a solid set of comfortable kickers although I wish they'd upgrade the straps.  I'm 6'3" tall an wear a XL as I do in just about all Castelli products.
review.name: Pretty Good Winter Knickers

review.reviewBody:
In general I'm a fan of Castelli winter bib tights and knickers as I think they provide good bang for the buck.  Castelli winter gear is even harder than normal to sort out for fit, but I have found lately going up 2 sizes works for me (size XL instead of my usual M for euro fit cycling gear).
Overall I liked the quality build of these knickers.  But the deal breaker was a large seam that comes up the back of the thigh, crosses the butt area, and continues down the other thigh.  The problem is the seam is quite thick (not flatlock), goes underneath the chamois, and for me just happens to cross right in that area of my sit bones and the business end back there, and I can feel it through the chamois.  I've never seen this on any pair of cycling bottoms (and I've ridden on a lot of them).
review.name: Nice quality but odd seam on backside

review.reviewBody:
I've had the original Castelli Nanoflex shorts for several years now and they've been perfect for high-50's to mid-60deg days where I might start w/ knee warmers and eventually take them off.  These Tutto Nano knickers slot in nicely between my Nanoflex shorts and wind-blocking bib tights since they are definitely warmer and more comfortable in the low to high 50's than my Nanoflex shorts plus knee warmers.  Just like my Nanoflex shorts I love the warmth and luxurious 2nd skin feel of Nanoflex lycra.

I have a small bicyclist's body (125lbs. & 29" waist) so it's a good thing that I too need to "size up" in Castelli bibs (a "Small" is supposedly for a 31.5" waist and they don't make a size XS which I need in most other brands' bibs).  However these fit a bit more loosely around my hips than my other Castelli bibs (including my Nanoflex bib shorts) so I'd call them closer to "true to size" than other Castelli bibs.  In particular the Sorpasso 2 bib knickers which I returned definitely have the tighter fit I prefer but the chamois' location was too far back for my sit bones (strange - I've never experienced this in a Castelli bib before).  Fortunately the chamois position in this Tutto Nano model is perfect and I find the Kiss Air2 model to be just as comfortable as Castelli's higher-end Progetto ones (and perhaps more long-lasting since I've found that the gel inserts in the Progetto chamois can "pack out" after only one season of riding).  

Other than the slightly looser fit (which might allow the chamois to move around when the material stretches out a bit more) I'm a bit torn about the Giro3 leg grippers.  They do work better and are more comfortable vs. the narrow gripper strips used on the Sorpasso's & most other knickers.  However the Giro3's are a 3" tall band of gripper material that provides no insulation, so these knickers expose more of your lower leg to the elements vs. other models.  They also don't have some of the Sorpasso's other higher-end features like lay-flat bib straps and (in the latest ROS version) NanoFlex Xtra Dry lycra panels in key areas for added warmth & water-repellency.  However I find that the Tutto Nano's seamed bib straps work fine since I always wear them over a medium wt. base layer, I don't ride much in the rain so the added water-repellency of the Xtra Dry lycra isn't a big loss, and if I need more warmth then I'd use my wind-blocking bib tights instead.  

These are near-perfect bib knickers especially given their price vs. the Sorpasso ROS's and most other brands' knickers (e.g., Assos, Giordana, Rapha...).  They are perfect for someone that finds the Sorpasso's fit to be too tight or otherwise not quite right and who wants the superior water-repellency that Nanoflex lycra is known for.
review.name: Very Nice!

review.reviewBody: My second pair. I have narrow feet and they're perfect for that. Toe box is roomy. The ventilation is amazing - I had a pair of Sidis before these and they were so heavy and hot in the summer. I do have to line my feet with plastic bags in the winter in these -- they're def not warm shoes! I love them and the fit is perfect for me.
review.name: Super light

review.reviewBody: This is the first pair of cycling shoes that doesn't give me any discomfort on long summer rides. They are, for me, extremely comfortable, with a roomy toe box and superb ventilation. I am EUR 45 with slightly wide feet and the fit is phenomenal. Having read other reviews, I try to be very gentle with the BOA system. I would not expect these shoes to be very useful for cooler whether.
review.name: Great Summer Shoes

review.reviewBody:
Shoes seem to be a very personal bit of cycling gear, like saddles.  What's perfect for everyone tends to vary, and sometimes by a lot.
I've had my original pair of imperials almost 4 years now (about 20k miles).  I've had many other good shoes but always some flaw that made me keep looking.  Most of my cycling is to try and stay race fit:  shorter interval rides plus one 3-5hr ride per week.  Mostly road but some mixed terrain and gravel/fire roads.  Some shoes felt great for racing crits but got miserable on longer and/or bumpy rides.  Others were great all day but didn't have that locked-in feeling I want in hard interval training or racing.  These imperials excel at both.  They also excel in a variety of weather conditions:  I've ridden these in temps down to high 30's, all the way up to a 110 degree roaster:  feet are always comfortable.  Yes feet get wet quick in rain, but they dry quick.  I've never had a pair of shoes that didn't turn into sloshy messes after 5min of rain, so quick drying is priority.  Also, after a messy rainy muddy ride these wipe down and clean up super easy, even in white!
Its worth noting a few things that other commenters have noted here too:

First, may be a little extra room if you use stock insoles and have normal or narrow width feet such that when you fully tighten the front boa dial the material at the top of the toe box will visually buckle:  doesn't effect the fit but its unsightly.  My custom insoles take up that extra space so it disappears.  If not using thicker insoles or higher arch support, there are these things called insole shims that are very cheap and can fill up the extra 2-3mm of space and completely eliminate this visual material buckling.  I actually appreciate that Giro left some wiggle room to allow for these options in fit.

Second:  I get toe rub on my front tire and no pair of shoes is immune to this.  A little bit of shoe goo as a protective layer on the toe tips and problem solved.

Third, boa dial durability.  Bottom line is not good:  design flaw on Boa's part.  My first pair had one Boa dial fail:  the screw mount of the part sewn into the shoe broke.  Contact Boa and they'll send replacement free.  But the replacement is just the dial and not broken part sewn into the shoe.  So I contacted Giro and within 24 hours they were on it and had a new pair in the mail to me as warranty replacements.  I was astounded.  Not only that, but their customer service was absolutely awesome to deal with!  This is what makes a company great.

This experience I had with the warranty replacement, plus the fact that these are just the best shoes I have ever owned in a cycling career of almost 20 years, gave me the comfort level to buy another pair.  And then another.  Yep, I own 3 pairs of these now.  Crazy?  Maybe.

A couple more tips on Boa dials in general.  First, when pulling the dial out to loosen the lace, make sure you pull straight back and don't wiggle the dial back and forth while pulling:  this weakens that already weak plastic post that the dial mounts to.  Second, if you do break the Boas you can contact Boa, explain the issue and maybe twist an arm or two, they will also send you free replacement of the part that sews into the shoe.  Once you have that piece, any good shoe repair shop can easily remove the old broken one and sew a new one in.  I know this because after the warranty replacement I had another Boa dial break.  Instead of trying the warranty route again (which I'm sure Giro would've honored) I decided to try this repair route and sure enough a local shoe repair shop took out the old one, sewed a new one in and $25 later the shoe was good as new;  another 4k comfy miles on it so far with many more to go.  Super easy, inexpensive and much less total waste.  Win, win and win.

Buy these.  Try them.  Odds are excellent that you won't be disappointed.
review.name: Worth every penny

review.reviewBody: I bought the red pair as a back up to the black pair in the same shoe. Love the ventilation. Love the style and adjustability. Love the overall fit, especially for my flat wide feet. But alas, after less than two years and very little use, the left front BOA snapped off. As near as I can tell it’s not replaceable as it is sewn into the shoe. I had a pair of Specialized S-works shoes that lasted more than 7 years. I even used the S-works sole in this shoe for better comfort. I expected more for $450.
review.name: Broken BOA

review.reviewBody:
I rode and raced in these shoes for about 2 years. They are awesome. I had them fitted with my bike fit and had some more supportive inserts put in for my arch support and less foot movement. 

They were great in hot Texas summer months. Long rides didn’t produce heat spots in these shoes as some other shoes had done in the past. Great ventilation probably helps. The obvious downside with the ventilation is that if it rains, your feet are getting wet really quick - even if you have shoe covers. 

In races, the shoes played their part. They were always stiff, responsive and just didn’t make think about shoes at all during a race. I never felt like I had a disadvantage - they were just a great racing shoe. 

Finally after 2 years of use, the BOA on the right shoe broke. That’s expected. I got thousands of miles from this shoe. I was actually thinking about retiring them and getting another pair anyway. Which is what I am doing - getting another pair. Great shoe.
review.name: Lasted 2 years

review.reviewBody:
I have narrow feet , B width and ordered size 45.5 EUR or 11.5 US - the initial fit felt pretty good but when I tightened the lower BOA dial the toe fabric/material buckled/puckered somewhat which could be due to my narrow feet .

I felt that these shoes were a little wide for my feet and returned them ,
review.name: First Impression of the Giro Imperial
comment: Thanks for the review, I suffer with trying to find proper fitting shoes with my narrow feet as well.

review.reviewBody:
This $450 shoe is everything you want in an elite cycling shoe, except the durability. 

After 1 k miles, the left sole broke at the toe clip during hard braking on a decent, sending me to the ground. However, before this, the shoe has been slowly deteriorating, with the white coating coming off piece by piece. 

The paper-thin EC90 sole has been very stiff, however, that comes at a huge cost, very disappointed in the longevity of these shoes.
review.name: Great Shoe...But Didn't Hold Up
comment: "the left sole broke at the toe clip during hard braking on a decent .." were you riding a fixie?

review.reviewBody:
Great breathability. Awesome sockless. Lightweight. Easy to get your foot in and out of.
Excellent hold on heel. Small toe box. May want to consider sizing up a your foot expands over longer distances.
review.name: Road shoe for IM

review.reviewBody: My arches have been falling in my 50s and so after 26 years on SiDi Genius models, I got the Imperials thinking they would have a lower stack height to allow arch-support insoles without messing up my position on the bike. So a few notes on the comparison: SIZING: exactly the same in my size 43. Feels like they are identical, down to the millimeter. WEIGHT: Genius 5 with nylon sole ad SPD-Sl cleats 352g each, the Imperial 262g.  STACK HEIGHT: even with the insoles it feels a bit shorter than the old SiDi with no insoles (that stack height was about 10mm). HEEL RETENTION: reviews mentioned this as a mild negative with the Imperial, but I found if anything that it was better than the SiDI when the Boa wires were snug. (I didn't find the wires stuck to the tongue either.)  SOLES: the carbon soles here actually seemed to give about as much as the old thick nylon SiDis -- which is to say, a tiny bit, but not much. the CLEAT HOLES seem to be possibly about 1mm further back than the SiDi holes .... All in all, an almost seamless transition. between brands, which was very surprising to me. The arch support inserts are terrific, they sit *under* the liner so they're fairly unobtrusive, and they seem to be helping a lot. My first pair of SiDis lasted 65,000 miles and it does seem like there's absolutely no way the Giros will last as long, the Teijin outer material is thin and it does scrape up pretty easily. BTW the mesh part is see-thru (see photo), so choose your socks well, but the ventilation is terrific in the heat. Comes with a nice zip bag to pack them up in. ... Mild irritations: the red color is far less saturated in daylight than it appears in the product shots. The Boa dials work in opposite directions on the left and right feet, kind of like prewar bathroom sink faucets. ... All in all, a terrific, thoughtfully designed product.
review.name: Seamless switch from SiDi
